Javalin uses [SLF4J][1] for logging (you can even see the class name `Slf4jLog` in the first message). This is an abstracton which can work with many different actual implementations, so the first step is to find which one your project uses. List the dependencies ([Gradle][2], [Maven][3]) and look for `slf4j-&lt;something&gt;` (except `slf4j-api`) or `logback-classic`. Then look at https://www.slf4j.org/manual.html#swapping for the one you found and find how to configure it to set to a higher level than `INFO`.

E.g. if you followed 

&gt; Javalin does not have a logger included, which means that you have to add your own logger. If you dont know/care a lot about Java loggers, the easiest way to fix this is to add the following dependency to your project:

&gt;     &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.slf4j&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;slf4j-simple&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;1.7.26&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;


from the Javalin documentation, see [How to configure slf4j-simple][4].


